    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>AIDS Drugs and Africa</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Geren Horsley says making AIDS drugs available at cheaper price in Africa is so logical that it is baffling that Congress blocked this legislation in past</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Making AIDS drugs available at a cheaper price in Africa (news article, May 11) is so logical that it baffles me that Congress has blocked this legislation in the past. President Clinton's use of executive orders can override the Congressional lobbyists and their financial interest.</p>
        <p>Along with AIDS, Africa is experiencing one of its worst periods of drought and civil war.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Making AIDS drugs available at a cheaper price in Africa (news article, May 11) is so logical that it baffles me that Congress has blocked this legislation in the past. President Clinton's use of executive orders can override the Congressional lobbyists and their financial interest.</p>
        <p>Along with AIDS, Africa is experiencing one of its worst periods of drought and civil war.</p>
        <p>We can afford to be the humanitarian nation we so often brag about to the world, and now is the time.</p>
        <p>GEREN  HORSLEY  Boston, May 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
